04445nam a22006975i 9780231538428DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20142014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014014340  a97802315384287 a10.7312/delg163002doi  a(DE-B1597)458303  a(OCoLC)979745772  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHV1451b.D45 2015 7aSOC0160002bisacsh04a305.21 aDelgado, Melvin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBaby Boomers of Color :bImplications for Social Work Policy and Practice /cMelvin Delgado. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b‹B›Figures: ‹/B›1.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tPart one. Setting the Context -- t1. Overview -- t2. Two Perspectives on Baby Boomers -- t3. Baby Boomer Demographic Profile and Trends -- t4. A Demographic Focus on Baby Boomers of Color -- t5. Health Needs -- t6. Financial Indicators -- tPart two. Cultural Assets -- t7. Baby Boomer Assets -- t8. Family-Focused Assets -- t9. Neighborhood/ Community-Focused Assets -- tPart three. Implications for Policy, Practice, and Research -- t10. Classification of Asset- Driven Interventions -- t11. Policy, Practice, and Research Implications -- tEpilogue -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBecause researchers often treat baby boomers of color as belonging to one group, quality data on the individual status of specific racial populations is lacking, leading to insufficiently designed programs, policies, and services. The absence of data is a testament to the invisibility of baby boomers of color in society and deeply affects the practice of social work and other helping professions that require culturally sensitive approaches. Melvin Delgado rectifies this injustice by providing a comprehensive portrait of the status and unique assets of boomers of color. Using specific data, he grounds an understanding of boomers'financial, medical, and emotional needs within a historical, socioeconomic, cultural, and political context, resulting in tailored recommendations for meeting the challenges of a growing population. His research focuses on African American, Hispanic, Asian/Pacific Islander, and Native American older adults and addresses issues of financial security, employment stability, housing, and health care, which are often complicated by linguistic and cultural differences. Rather than treat baby boomers of color as a financial burden on society and its resources, Delgado recognizes their strengths and positive contributions to families and communities, resulting in an affirming and empowering approach to service.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aBaby boom generation. 0aMinority older people. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Human Services.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066586440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/delg1630040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231538428423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231538428/original  a978-3-11-066586-4  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK